In Lean 4, the notation `∀ᵐ x, P x` is defined as `∀ x, P x` with the quantifier being "almost all" instead of "for all". The definition uses the concept of "almost all" with respect to a measure. In the case of `ℝ` with the Lebesgue measure, it means that the set of rational numbers has measure zero.

To prove this, we can use the fact that the set of rational numbers is countable. In `ℝ`, any countable set has Lebesgue measure zero. Therefore, the set of rational numbers, being countable, has measure zero. This implies that the set of irrational numbers has measure equal to the measure of `ℝ` (which is infinite).

